{"parse":{"title":"Operation Bloodstone","pageid":40194846,"revid":852056312,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Operation Bloodstone</b> was a <a href=\"/wiki/Covert_operation\" title=\"Covert operation\">covert operation</a> whereby the <a href=\"/wiki/Central_Intelligence_Agency\" title=\"Central Intelligence Agency\">Central Intelligence Agency</a> (CIA) sought out <a href=\"/wiki/Nazis\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Nazis\">Nazis</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Nazi_collaborators\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Nazi collaborators\">collaborators</a> living in Soviet-controlled areas, to work undercover for U.S. intelligence inside of the <a href=\"/wiki/Soviet_Union\" title=\"Soviet Union\">Soviet Union</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Latin_America\" title=\"Latin America\">Latin America</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Canada\" title=\"Canada\">Canada</a>, as well as domestically within the <a href=\"/wiki/United_States\" title=\"United States\">United States</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> \n</p><p>Many of those who were hired as part of Bloodstone were high-ranking Nazi intelligence agents who had committed <a href=\"/wiki/War_crimes\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"War crimes\">war crimes</a>. Operation Bloodstone was initially proposed by the <a href=\"/wiki/U.S._State_Department\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"U.S. State Department\">U.S. State Department</a>, and was approved by SANACC (the State, Army, Navy, Air Force Coordinating Committee) on June 10, 1948. In July, SANACC expanded the operation to:<sup id=\"cite_ref-Gerolymatos-2010-p144_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Gerolymatos-2010-p144-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<blockquote><p><i>\"comprise those activities against the enemy which are conducted by Allied or friendly forces behind enemy lines ... [to] include <a href=\"/wiki/Psychological_warfare\" title=\"Psychological warfare\">psychological warfare</a>, subversion, <a href=\"/wiki/Sabotage\" title=\"Sabotage\">sabotage</a>, and miscellaneous operations such as <a href=\"/wiki/Assassination\" title=\"Assassination\">assassination</a>, target capture and rescue of Allied airmen.\"</i></p></blockquote>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Operation_Bloodstone&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Klaus_Barbie\" title=\"Klaus Barbie\">Klaus Barbie</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Operation_Paperclip\" title=\"Operation Paperclip\">Operation Paperclip</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Ratlines_(World_War_II)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Ratlines (World War II)\">Ratlines (World War II)</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/U.S._intelligence_involvement_with_German_and_Japanese_war_criminals_after_World_War_II\" title=\"U.S. intelligence involvement with German and Japanese war criminals after World War II\">U.S. intelligence involvement with German and Japanese war criminals after World War II</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Operation_Bloodstone&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Valentine, Douglas (2004). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=Bed0gQKn-ucC&amp;pg=PA100\"><i>The Strength of the Wolf: The Secret History of America's War on Drugs</i></a>. Verso. p.&#160;100. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/9781859845684\" title=\"Special:BookSources/9781859845684\">9781859845684</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Strength+of+the+Wolf%3A+The+Secret+History+of+America%27s+War+on+Drugs&amp;rft.pages=100&amp;rft.pub=Verso&amp;rft.date=2004&amp;rft.isbn=9781859845684&amp;rft.au=Valentine%2C+Douglas&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DBed0gQKn-ucC%26pg%3DPA100&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AOperation+Bloodstone\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Wilford, Hugh (2009). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=n3Ol_XDmPdsC&amp;pg=PA29\"><i>The Mighty Wurlitzer: How the CIA Played America</i></a>. Harvard University Press. pp.&#160;29\u201330. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780674045170\" title=\"Special:BookSources/9780674045170\">9780674045170</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Mighty+Wurlitzer%3A+How+the+CIA+Played+America&amp;rft.pages=29-30&amp;rft.pub=Harvard+University+Press&amp;rft.date=2009&amp;rft.isbn=9780674045170&amp;rft.au=Wilford%2C+Hugh&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3Dn3Ol_XDmPdsC%26pg%3DPA29&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AOperation+Bloodstone\" class=\